		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Qu&agrave;m diu iocabatur &AElig;sopus, successum est ei
						foeliciter: cum primu[m]
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Aesop"/>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						seri&ograve; agebat, et sua[e] est oblitus ingeniosa[e]
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Ironia[e], statim perijt miserrim&egrave;.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				As long as he was joking, Aesop happily found success;
				when he first acted seriously, and forgot his own ingenious irony,
				immediately he perished miserably.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Aut
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						non erant prouocandi
						Delphici sacerdotes:
						aut ita tractandi, vt poste&agrave; agebat Socrates
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Socrates"/>
					<location name="Delphi"/>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						cum sophistis quos laudans
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						rearguebat; redarguens laudabant.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Probo arguta apophthegmata, dicteria, problemata:
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						epigrammata, satyras: sed conditas salibus,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						et iocis:
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						quorum est in omni stylo,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						et sermone
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						perpetuus vsus. Nec vlla ars
						pra[e]gnantior,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						aut frequentior in humana vita, qu&agrave;m ha[e]c ciuilium
						Iocorum.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				But the priests of Delphi should not have been provoked, or even negotiated with,
				as Socrates did, afterwards, with the sophists, whom he refuted through praise.
				In turn, they praised him through refutation.
				
				I approve clever aphorisms, sayings, problems, epigrams, satires,
				but all seasoned with wit and jokes, the continual use of which can be
				found in every style and language. No art is more pregnant and frequent
				in human life, than that of civil joking.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Idea in manu.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The idea in hand.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
					<marginalia_text>
						Doctoris est docere: aliorum discere. Illius superare: horum submitti. 
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The job of learned men is to teach, of other men to learn. The former overcome, the latter submit.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
